 “One challenge I faced was related to securing our CI/CD pipeline using GitHub OIDC roles. We had separate environments like pre-prod and production, and deployments required peer review before applying changes.

Initially, we used a single IAM role for both Terraform plan and apply, and the trust policy allowed access using a broad subject claim like repo:*. We relied on pipeline conditions to ensure that apply only runs from the main branch.

However, this introduced a security risk. If a GitHub account was compromised or the pipeline condition was bypassed, someone could potentially trigger apply from another branch and make destructive changes.

To solve this, I separated the roles into two: one for plan and one for apply. The plan role retained broader access since it only performs read operations. For the apply role, I restricted the trust policy by setting the subject claim specifically to the main branch using repo:owner/repo:ref:refs/heads/main.

This ensured that even if pipeline conditions were altered, AWS would only allow apply operations from the main branch, adding an extra layer of security at the IAM level.”

