“In addition to that, we had different deployment strategies for environments. For dev and test, we allowed automated deployments at the pull request level. However, for pre-production and production, deployments required manual approval and were not fully automated.

To handle this securely, we used GitHub Environments along with OIDC. We created two roles: github-actions-plan and github-actions-apply. The plan role had a broader subject claim since it only performed read operations.

For the apply role, instead of allowing all branches, we restricted access using the subject claim with environment:<environment-name>. This ensured that deployments could only happen through approved GitHub environments.

Additionally, we enforced protected branches in GitHub to prevent bypassing approval workflows. This way, even if someone tried to bypass pipeline conditions, AWS IAM and GitHub environment protections together ensured that only authorized and approved deployments could be executed.”